"""Short-form "What is X?" paraphrases for major topics. Fixes retrieval gap where short queries miss long-key corpus entries."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is PCA?','Principal Component Analysis. Find directions of max variance in data. Project onto top-K components → reduce dimensions while preserving most info. Steps: center data, compute covariance, find eigenvectors (or SVD). Use for: visualization (project to 2D), feature reduction, denoising, exploratory analysis. Limitations: linear, sensitive to scale (always normalize first).'),
    ('What is FFT?','Fast Fourier Transform: converts time-domain signal to frequency-domain in O(n log n). Use for: filtering noise (zero out frequencies + inverse), spectral analysis, fast convolution (multiply in freq domain), audio/image processing. numpy.fft + scipy.fft. Pick power of 2 length for max speed (zero-pad if needed).'),
    ('What is SVD?','Singular Value Decomposition. Factorize matrix A = U Σ V^T where U + V are orthonormal and Σ is diagonal of singular values sorted descending. Used in: PCA (Σ² gives variance), low-rank approximation, pseudo-inverse, recommender systems (Netflix prize), latent semantic analysis.'),
    ('What is BFS?','Breadth-first search. Explore graph level-by-level using a queue. Finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. Uses O(width) memory. Best for: shortest path in unweighted graph, level-by-level traversal, finding closest nodes from a source.'),
    ('What is DFS?','Depth-first search. Explore graph by going deep before backtracking, using a stack or recursion. Uses O(depth) memory. Best for: detecting cycles, computing topological order, finding connected components, exhaustive search.'),
    ('What is Cassandra?','Apache Cassandra — wide-column distributed database. Linearly scalable writes (no single primary). Eventual consistency tunable per query (ONE/QUORUM/ALL). Best for: massive write throughput, time-series, IoT sensor data, write-heavy workloads. Not for: ad-hoc queries (no JOIN), complex transactions, low data volumes.'),
    ('What is Spanner?','Google Spanner — globally-distributed strongly-consistent SQL database. Uses TrueTime (atomic clocks + GPS) for externally consistent transactions across regions. SQL interface, ACID, horizontal scale. Powers Gmail, AdWords. Open equivalents: CockroachDB, YugabyteDB.'),
    ('What is asyncio?','Python\'s standard async I/O library. Single-threaded cooperative concurrency via coroutines and an event loop. Use for: I/O-bound work (network, disk) — overlap waits. asyncio.run(main()) runs a coroutine. async def + await are the syntax. Use asyncio.gather / asyncio.create_task to fan out work.'),
    ('What is asyncawait?','Async/await: syntactic sugar over promises/futures for cooperative concurrency. `async function f() { const x = await otherPromise; ... }`. await pauses until promise settles, returning value or throwing. async fns always return Promises (JS) / coroutines (Python). Critical: don\'t mix with blocking calls inside async functions — freezes the event loop.'),
    ('What is async await?','See async/await: syntactic sugar over Promises (JS) or coroutines (Python). Lets you write asynchronous code that reads like synchronous code. await suspends execution until the awaited value is ready. Foundation of modern non-blocking I/O patterns.'),
    ('What is cache stampede?','Specific thundering herd: cache miss → many concurrent requests recompute the same value simultaneously, overwhelming the backend. Fix: (1) lock — only one request recomputes, others wait or return stale. (2) probabilistic early expiration — refresh BEFORE expiry randomly. (3) stale-while-revalidate — serve stale while async refresh runs.'),
    ('What is the Maybe monad?','Wraps optional values: Just(x) or Nothing (Some/None depending on language). Forces handling absence at type level. flatMap chains: `getUser().flatMap(getProfile).flatMap(getEmail)` — short-circuits at first Nothing. Replaces null checks scattered everywhere. Modern languages bake this in: Rust Option, Swift Optional, Haskell Maybe.'),
    ('What is REST?','Representational State Transfer. HTTP-based API style using nouns (resources) + standard verbs (GET/POST/PUT/DELETE). Stateless. Common mistakes: verbs in URLs (/getUser/5 vs GET /users/5), ignoring HTTP status codes, no versioning. REST is convention as much as protocol.'),
    ('What is GraphQL?','Query language for APIs. Single endpoint, client specifies exactly which fields it wants (no over/under-fetching). Strongly typed schema. Cons vs REST: caching harder, complexity in resolver perf (N+1 risk), server complexity higher. Use for: rich UIs with varied data needs. REST often simpler for typical CRUD.'),
    ('What is gRPC?','RPC framework using HTTP/2 + Protocol Buffers. Strongly typed via .proto files; codegen generates client + server stubs. Supports: unary, server streaming, client streaming, bidirectional streaming. Faster + smaller than JSON over HTTP. Best for: service-to-service comms. Browser support requires gRPC-Web.'),
    ('What is OAuth?','OAuth 2.0 — authorization framework. Lets users grant third-party apps limited access to their account WITHOUT sharing the password. User → consents → owner gives app a TOKEN representing limited access. Token expires + can be revoked. OAuth is AUTHORIZATION; OIDC adds authentication on top.'),
    ('What is OIDC?','OpenID Connect — authentication layer on top of OAuth 2.0. Adds an ID token (JWT containing user identity claims) so the app KNOWS who the user is. "Sign in with Google" is OIDC. Use OIDC for user login flows.'),
    ('What is JWT?','JSON Web Token. Three parts (header, payload, signature) joined by dots, base64url-encoded. Self-contained: server can verify validity WITHOUT a database lookup. Use for: stateless API auth, short-lived access tokens. Don\'t store sensitive data (payload is base64 — readable, not encrypted by default). Verify with proper algorithm — never accept "alg: none."'),
    ('What is TLS?','Transport Layer Security. Encrypts + authenticates network communication. Modern: TLS 1.3 (2018). Provides: confidentiality (encryption), integrity (HMAC), server identity (cert chain). HTTPS = HTTP + TLS. Handshake uses asymmetric crypto to agree on symmetric session key. Forward secrecy via ephemeral key exchange.'),
    ('What is SSL?','Secure Sockets Layer — older name for what is now TLS (Transport Layer Security). Strictly: SSL versions all deprecated; "SSL" colloquially means TLS today. SSL certs = TLS certs. Use TLS 1.2 or 1.3 in production; older versions have known weaknesses.'),
    ('What is a vector database?','Stores embeddings (high-dim vectors) + supports approximate-nearest-neighbor search. Query: encode query → vector → find closest stored vectors. Examples: Pinecone, Weaviate, Qdrant, Milvus, pgvector. Used for: semantic search, RAG, dedup, recommendation.'),
    ('What is an embedding?','Dense vector representation of text/image/etc that places semantically similar items close together. Computed by an embedding model. 384-3072 dims typical. Use cosine similarity to compare. Foundation of RAG retrieval and semantic search.'),
    ('What is fine-tuning?','Train a pretrained model further on task-specific data to specialize it. Updates weights permanently. Requires labeled data + compute. Alternatives: in-context learning (no training, examples in prompt), PEFT (train only a small subset of weights via LoRA etc).'),
    ('What is a transformer?','Neural network architecture built around attention. Each token computes weighted combinations of all other tokens via Query/Key/Value projections. Parallelizable across sequence length. Stacked layers + residual connections. Foundation of GPT, BERT, Claude, Llama, and most modern LLMs.'),
    ('What is attention in NLP?','Mechanism letting each token in a sequence compute a weighted sum over all other tokens. Weights determined by query·key dot product. Self-attention: Q,K,V from same input. Cross-attention: Q from one source, K,V from another. Multi-head: do attention multiple times in parallel with different projections.'),
    ('What is overfitting?','Model memorizes training data instead of learning general patterns. Symptom: training accuracy ≫ validation accuracy. Fixes: more data, regularization (L1/L2, dropout, weight decay), simpler model, early stopping, data augmentation. Always hold out a clean test set you never train on.'),
    ('What is gradient descent?','Iterative optimization to minimize a loss function. Compute gradient (slope) at current parameters, step in opposite direction (downhill), repeat. Step size = learning rate. Stochastic gradient descent (SGD) uses mini-batches. Adam, AdaGrad, RMSprop are adaptive variants.'),
    ('What is backpropagation?','Algorithm computing gradients in neural networks via chain rule. Forward pass: compute predictions + loss. Backward pass: from loss, recursively compute gradient w.r.t. each weight using chain rule. Cost: ~2x forward pass. Standard in all modern deep learning frameworks (autograd).'),
    ('What is Docker?','Containerization platform. Package app + dependencies + OS bits into an image; run as a container (isolated process). Same image runs anywhere Docker runs. Built from a Dockerfile (recipe). Run with `docker run`. Compose multiple containers with docker-compose. Production: Kubernetes orchestrates.'),
    ('What is Kubernetes?','Container orchestrator. You declare desired state ("run 3 replicas of this image with this config"); K8s makes it so. Schedules containers across nodes, restarts failed ones, load-balances traffic, auto-scales, rolls out new versions safely. Steep learning curve. Overkill for a single app on one server.'),
    ('What is a pod?','Smallest unit in Kubernetes — one or more co-located containers sharing network + storage. Usually one container per pod. Pods are ephemeral; controllers (Deployments, StatefulSets) manage their lifecycle.'),
    ('What is CI?','Continuous Integration. Every code push automatically builds + tests. Fast feedback to developers. Tools: GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, CircleCI, Jenkins. Pair with CD (Continuous Delivery/Deployment) to also auto-deploy passing builds.'),
    ('What is CD?','Continuous Delivery (always deployable) OR Continuous Deployment (every passing commit auto-deploys to prod). Requires: high test coverage, monitoring, easy rollback. Pair with CI. Modern shift: trunk-based dev + feature flags decouple deploy from release.'),
    ('What is TDD?','Test-Driven Development. Write a failing test FIRST, then write minimum code to make it pass, then refactor. Cycle: red-green-refactor. Forces you to think about API + edge cases before implementation. Not always practical (exploratory code, prototypes), but produces well-tested code when applied.'),
    ('What is DRY?','Don\'t Repeat Yourself. Every piece of knowledge has a single authoritative representation. Failure mode: over-applying to coincidental similarity — two pieces of code that LOOK alike but represent different concepts. When concepts diverge, the shared abstraction becomes a tangle. Better rule: WET — don\'t DRY out until you see the same knowledge in three places.'),
    ('What is SOLID?','Five OO design principles. Single Responsibility (one reason to change per class). Open/Closed (open for extension, closed for modification). Liskov Substitution (subclass usable wherever parent is). Interface Segregation (many small interfaces > one big). Dependency Inversion (depend on abstractions, not concretions).'),
    ('What is KISS?','Keep It Simple, Stupid. Simplicity is a feature. Complex abstraction without proven need = future maintenance burden. Default to obvious solutions; deviate consciously when complexity buys something.'),
    ('What is YAGNI?','You Aren\'t Gonna Need It. Don\'t build features speculatively. Add complexity only when you have THREE concrete cases that need it. Premature flexibility creates the wrong abstraction. Speculative features have carrying cost (test, maintain, doc, security implications) even unused.'),
    ('What is MVP?','Minimum Viable Product. Smallest version of a product that delivers value to users, ships to learn. Goal: validate assumptions with real users fast. Not "half-baked thing" — must be VIABLE. Iterate from there based on what users actually want, not what you guessed.'),
    ('What is a microservice?','Small independently-deployable service that owns a specific bounded context. Communicates with others via APIs (REST, gRPC) or messaging. Use when: org large enough that teams need to deploy independently, scaling needs differ per service. Don\'t use for small teams — monoliths are simpler and faster.'),
    ('What is a monolith?','Application deployed as a single unit. All features in one codebase + database + process. Easier to develop + deploy + debug than microservices. Hard to scale teams + scale specific parts. Most apps should start as monolith; extract microservices later if pain forces it.'),
    ('What is technical debt?','Accumulated cost of expedient decisions that need rework. Like financial debt: small amounts can be useful (ship fast); too much compounds and slows everything down. Pay down: regular refactoring, dedicated time, "boy scout rule" (leave code cleaner). Track explicitly; don\'t pretend it isn\'t there.'),
    ('What is dependency injection?','Pass dependencies into a class/function rather than constructing them inside. Instead of `def f(): db = Database()`, do `def f(db)`. Benefits: testable (inject mocks), composable (swap implementations), explicit (clear what a function needs).'),
    ('What is mocking?','Replace real dependencies with controllable fakes during tests. Lets you test code in isolation. Mock at the boundary you control. Python: unittest.mock. JS: jest.mock. Don\'t over-mock — too many mocks = brittle tests that pass with bugs.'),
    ('What is a unit test?','Tests one function/class in isolation, fast, lots of them. Should be deterministic (no flakes), targeted (one behavior), self-explaining (failure msg tells you what was expected). Anti-pattern: tests with lots of setup + multiple assertions.'),
    ('What is integration test?','Tests how multiple units work together, often with real dependencies (DB, API, queue). Slower than unit but catches integration bugs unit tests miss. Modern shift: heavy on integration tests, lighter on units (trophy model).'),
    ('What is end-to-end test?','Tests the whole system through the UI as a user would. Tools: Cypress, Playwright. Slowest, flakiest, most expensive — keep few. Use to verify critical user journeys (signup, checkout, etc).'),
    ('What is a load balancer?','Distributes incoming traffic across multiple backend servers. Algorithms: round-robin, least-connections, IP-hash, latency-based. Levels: L4 (TCP, fast, simple) vs L7 (HTTP, smart routing). Examples: nginx, HAProxy, AWS ALB, Cloudflare. Critical for: horizontal scale, fault tolerance, zero-downtime deploys.'),
    ('What is a CDN?','Content Delivery Network. Replicas of static content at points-of-presence near users. DNS routes users to nearest POP. Lower latency, less load on origin, DDoS absorption. Examples: Cloudflare, Fastly, AWS CloudFront, BunnyCDN. Modern CDNs run logic at edge too (Workers, Lambda@Edge).'),
    ('What is a reverse proxy?','Server in front of backend servers, accepting client requests and forwarding to backends. Adds: TLS termination, caching, rate limiting, load balancing, auth. Examples: nginx, Caddy, Traefik, Envoy. Different from forward proxy (sits in front of client).'),
    ('What is a webhook?','HTTP callback. Server A notifies Server B of an event by making an HTTP request to a URL B provided. Examples: GitHub notifying CI of a push, Stripe notifying app of a payment. Async + decoupled vs polling. Security: verify signature (HMAC) since URLs may be guessable.'),
    ('What is idempotency?','Operation that produces the same result whether called once or many times. PUT, GET, DELETE are idempotent; POST is not. Critical because networks fail + retries happen. Design ops to be idempotent (use client-supplied IDs, idempotency keys like Stripe pattern).'),
    ('What is rate limiting?','Cap requests per second/minute/hour per actor. Prevents brute force, scraping, DoS, runaway bots. Algorithms: token bucket, sliding window, fixed window. Implement at gateway (closer to client). Return 429 with Retry-After header.'),
    ('What is throttling?','Slowing down or rejecting requests when a limit is reached. Often used interchangeably with rate limiting. Implementations: token bucket (smooth bursts), leaky bucket (constant rate), fixed quotas.'),
    ('What is a circuit breaker?','Pattern preventing cascading failures. After threshold of failures calling a dependency, "open" the circuit — fail fast without calling for a timeout. Then "half-open" briefly to test recovery. Stops slow deps from consuming threads. Libraries: Hystrix, resilience4j, Polly.'),
    ('What is a bulkhead?','Pattern isolating resources so failure in one part doesn\'t consume all resources. Example: separate thread pools per downstream dependency — one slow dep can\'t exhaust all threads. Named after ship bulkheads that contain flooding.'),
    ('What is a retry pattern?','Reattempt failed operations. Best practice: exponential backoff (wait 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s...), jitter (random offset prevents synchronized waves), cap attempts (don\'t retry forever), only retry idempotent operations. Tools: tenacity (Python), retry libraries, AWS SDK built-in.'),
    ('What is a feature flag?','Conditional toggle that enables/disables a feature without redeploying. Use for: gradual rollout (10%, 50%, 100%), A/B testing, kill switch, dark launches. Decouples deploy from release. Tools: LaunchDarkly, GrowthBook, Unleash, Statsig. Clean up old flags or they accumulate.'),
    ('What is blue-green deployment?','Stand up new version (green) alongside old (blue). Switch traffic atomically once green is healthy. Rollback = switch back. Needs 2x capacity briefly. Lower-risk than in-place upgrade. Compare canary (gradual % shift).'),
    ('What is canary deployment?','Send small % of traffic (5%, then 25%, 100%) to new version, watch metrics, abort if errors spike. Slower than blue-green but lower risk for serious issues. Pair with automated rollback on metric regression.'),
    ('What is observability?','Ability to investigate NEW questions about system behavior without adding new instrumentation. Three pillars: logs (text events), metrics (numeric over time), traces (request flow). Beyond just monitoring (predefined alerts). Modern stacks: OpenTelemetry instruments; Datadog/Grafana/Honeycomb store.'),
    ('What is monitoring?','Continuously watching system state and alerting on known failure modes. Dashboards (current state), alerts (something went wrong). Smaller subset of observability — you knew to ask the question in advance. Effective monitoring requires good alert hygiene (no false positives).'),
    ('What is a log?','Timestamped text event. Structured logs (JSON) preferred over plain text for filtering/aggregation. Include: timestamp, level, service, request_id, error+stack. Tools: Loki, Elasticsearch, Datadog. Don\'t log secrets or PII.'),
    ('What is tracing?','Distributed tracing — track a single request through multiple services with per-step timing. Each operation = span; spans form a tree per trace. Use to find latency in distributed systems. Tools: OpenTelemetry (instrumentation), Jaeger/Tempo/Datadog (storage + UI).'),
    ('What is a metric?','Numeric measurement over time. Examples: request rate, error rate, latency p95, queue length. Cheap to store. Used for dashboards, alerts, capacity planning. Tools: Prometheus, Grafana, Datadog, InfluxDB. Always cite percentiles (p50, p95, p99) — averages hide tail behavior.'),
    ('What is SLA?','Service Level Agreement. Contractual commitment to customers with penalties if missed. Typically: uptime % (99.9% = 8.76h/year downtime), response time. Differs from SLO (internal target, no penalty) and SLI (the measurement itself).'),
    ('What is SLO?','Service Level Objective. Internal target for reliability. Example: "99.9% of requests under 200ms over 28 days." Drives engineering priority — when error budget consumed, freeze features and fix reliability. Differs from SLA (contractual, customer-facing).'),
    ('What is SLI?','Service Level Indicator. A measurement of user experience. Example: "% of requests under 200ms." SLIs are what you measure; SLOs are targets for them; SLAs are contractual promises about them.'),
    ('What is a TCP socket?','Endpoint for TCP communication. Identified by (local IP, local port, remote IP, remote port) tuple. Server listens on a port; clients connect; OS allocates ephemeral local port for client. Each unique connection has its own socket.'),
    ('What is HTTPS?','HTTP wrapped in TLS encryption. Provides: confidentiality (encrypted bytes), integrity (tamper detection), server identity verification (cert chain). Doesn\'t protect: server-side data, metadata (DNS leaks site visits pre-ECH). Standard for modern web; browsers increasingly block plain HTTP.'),
    ('What is HTTP/2?','Newer HTTP version. Binary protocol over single TCP connection. Multiplexed streams (multiple requests in flight). HPACK header compression. Server push (mostly deprecated now). Still TCP — one packet loss blocks all streams (HOL blocking). HTTP/3 fixes this via QUIC.'),
    ('What is HTTP/3?','Built on QUIC (UDP-based). Proper stream isolation (no HOL blocking across streams). Faster connection setup (1-RTT vs 2-3 for TCP+TLS). Connection migration (survives IP change). Modern web increasingly HTTP/3.'),
    ('What is QUIC?','Transport protocol on UDP. Combines TLS 1.3 + multiplexing + connection migration. 0-RTT or 1-RTT setup. Per-stream HOL blocking elimination. Foundation of HTTP/3. Designed by Google, now IETF standard.'),
    ('What is WebSocket?','Bidirectional protocol over TCP. Persistent connection after HTTP upgrade. Binary or text frames. Use for: chat, multiplayer games, live updates, anything needing server-push. Modern alternative emerging: WebTransport (over QUIC, multiplexed streams).'),
    ('What is webRTC?','WebRTC — browser-native peer-to-peer real-time comms: audio, video, data channels. NAT traversal via STUN+TURN+ICE. Encryption mandatory (DTLS-SRTP). Used by: video calls, screen share, P2P file transfer, multiplayer games. Signaling protocol up to you.'),
    ('What is BFS algorithm?','Breadth-first search. Explore graph level-by-level using a queue. Each level\'s neighbors enqueued before going deeper. Finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. O(V+E). Uses O(width) memory.'),
    ('What is DFS algorithm?','Depth-first search. Explore graph by going as deep as possible before backtracking. Uses stack (or recursion). Finds: cycles, topological order, connected components, paths. O(V+E). Uses O(depth) memory.'),
    ('What is a B-tree?','Self-balancing tree where each node has many children (typically 16-1024). Designed for disk-based storage where reading one node = one disk I/O. Foundation of most database indexes (Postgres, MySQL InnoDB). B+tree variant: data only in leaves, internal nodes are keys only.'),
    ('What is an LRU cache?','Least Recently Used. Bounded cache that evicts the item not used for longest when full. Implementation: hash map + doubly-linked list (O(1) get + put). Python: functools.lru_cache decorator. Use for: memoization, query caches, anything with bounded working set.'),
    ('What is a bloom filter?','Probabilistic data structure for set membership. Fast + memory-efficient. False positives possible (says "in set" when not); never false negatives. Use for: cache filtering ("don\'t bother querying — definitely not there"), URL deduplication, network protocols. Configurable false positive rate by sizing.'),
    ('What is a Merkle tree?','Tree of hashes where each non-leaf node = hash of its children. Lets you efficiently verify large data hasn\'t been tampered with — only need root hash + small proof per item. Use cases: Git (commits hash trees), Bitcoin (transaction integrity), distributed databases (anti-entropy sync).'),
    ('What is a trie?','Tree where each path from root to a node spells a prefix. Each node has up to alphabet-size children. Use for: autocomplete (find all words with prefix X), spell checking, IP routing tables. Space-time trade vs hash set: supports prefix queries but uses more memory. Variant: compressed trie (Radix).'),
    ('What is binary search?','Sorted array. Maintain low/high pointers. Compute mid = (low+high)//2. If arr[mid] == target, found. If less, search right half. Else left half. O(log n) time, O(1) space. Variants: lower_bound (first ≥ target), upper_bound (first > target), binary search on answer for monotonic predicates.'),
    ('What is quicksort?','Pick a pivot. Partition: elements < pivot go left, > pivot go right. Recurse on each partition. Best/average O(n log n). Worst O(n²) on already-sorted with naive pivot — mitigated by random pivot. In-place. Not stable. Used by most language stdlibs underneath.'),
    ('What is mergesort?','Divide array into halves, recursively sort each, merge sorted halves. Stable. Guaranteed O(n log n). Needs O(n) extra space. Good for linked lists (no random access needed). Underlies external sorting for data too big to fit in memory.'),
    ('What is recursion?','Function calls itself with a smaller subproblem until base case. Use for: tree/graph traversal, divide-and-conquer, problems with self-similar structure. Watch for: clear base case, progress toward base case, stack depth limits. Tail recursion in some languages is optimized to iteration.'),
    ('What is memoization?','Cache function results for previously-seen inputs. Trade memory for time. Python: `@functools.lru_cache` or `@cache` for pure functions. Args must be hashable. Best for: recursive algorithms with overlapping subproblems (DP, Fibonacci, tree traversal).'),
    ('What is a stack?','LIFO (Last In First Out) data structure. Push to top, pop from top. Use for: function call frames, undo, backtracking, parsing, DFS, evaluating expressions. Python: list (append/pop), collections.deque. Stack overflow = recursion too deep.'),
    ('What is a queue?','FIFO (First In First Out) data structure. Enqueue at back, dequeue from front. Use for: BFS, task processing, event handling. Python: collections.deque (fast both ends). Don\'t use list (pop(0) is O(n)). Distributed: RabbitMQ, Kafka, SQS.'),
    ('What is a heap?','Tree-based priority queue. Min-heap: parent ≤ children. Max-heap: opposite. O(log n) insert/extract, O(1) peek. Implementation: array (parent at i, children at 2i+1, 2i+2). Python: heapq (min-heap; negate for max). Use for: k-largest, scheduling, Dijkstra\'s.'),
    ('What is OOP?','Object-Oriented Programming. Bundles data (attributes) + behavior (methods) into objects. Pillars: encapsulation (hide internals), inheritance (subclass extends parent), polymorphism (override methods), abstraction. Languages: Java, Python, C++, Swift. Modern advice: favor composition over inheritance.'),
    ('What is functional programming?','Programming paradigm emphasizing: pure functions (no side effects), immutability (data doesn\'t change), higher-order functions, recursion over loops, declarative over imperative. Pros: easier to reason, parallelize, test. Languages: Haskell, F#, Elixir, Scala. Patterns adopted by mainstream langs (JS, Python, Rust).'),
    ('What is a closure?','Function that captures variables from its enclosing scope, accessible even after that scope returns. JS: `function makeAdder(x) { return y => x + y }`. Use for: factory functions, private state, callbacks needing context, partial application.'),
    ('What is a generator?','Function with `yield` that produces values lazily. Each call advances to the next yield, pausing in between. Saves memory for large/infinite sequences. Python: `def gen(): yield 1; yield 2`. Use with: for-loops, list(), sum(), itertools pipelines.'),
    ('What is a decorator?','Function that wraps another function with extra behavior. Python: `@decorator` syntax. Common uses: logging, timing, caching (lru_cache), input validation, retries, permission checks. Don\'t hide important behavior — makes stack traces harder.'),
    ('What is a context manager?','Object with __enter__ and __exit__ methods used with `with` statement. Guarantees cleanup (file close, lock release, transaction commit) even on exception. Write your own with `@contextmanager` decorator + try/yield/finally.'),
    ('What is dependency injection in plain words?','Pass things your code needs INTO it, rather than creating them inside. Like: `def make_pizza(oven)` instead of `def make_pizza(): oven = Oven()`. Lets you swap (real oven vs test mock), explicit about needs, modular.'),
    ('What is a coroutine?','Function that can pause and resume. async/await syntax in most modern languages. Lighter than threads (no OS scheduler). Cooperative: function decides when to yield (no preemption). Foundation of async I/O.'),
    ('What is a thread?','Lightweight unit of execution sharing a process\'s memory + open files. Cheap to create vs processes. Communicates via shared variables (with locks) or message passing. Python: GIL means only one thread runs Python bytecode at a time — only helps for I/O-bound work.'),
    ('What is a process?','OS-level isolated execution with its own memory space. More expensive than threads. Communicates via IPC (pipes, sockets, shared memory). Python multiprocessing for true CPU parallelism (bypasses GIL). Each process can have multiple threads.'),
    ('What is the GIL?','Python\'s Global Interpreter Lock. Only one Python thread executes bytecode at a time. Affects CPU-bound work (threads don\'t give parallelism — use multiprocessing). Doesn\'t affect I/O-bound (GIL releases during I/O). Free-threaded Python 3.13+ removes it (experimental).'),
    ('What is REPL?','Read-Eval-Print Loop. Interactive shell where you type code, see result immediately. Python: `python` or `ipython`. JS: `node`. Useful for: exploration, debugging, learning. Jupyter notebook = REPL with rich output.'),
    ('What is a syscall?','Request to OS kernel from userspace. Mode switch from user → kernel ring, kernel handles, returns. Cost: context switch overhead (~50-1000ns). Common: open/read/write/close, mmap, fork, sockets. Heavy syscalls per request hurts throughput.'),
    ('What is virtual memory?','Each process sees its own contiguous address space; OS+MMU map it to physical RAM (or disk). Benefits: process isolation, memory protection, overcommit, swapping, copy-on-write. Cost: page table walks (TLB caches recent translations). Page fault: accessed memory not in RAM.'),
]
